# LXS node environment — copy to /etc/lxs/lxs.env, EDIT, then `chmod 600`.
#
# This file is the ONLY place the RPC API key lives. It is read by the binary
# from the environment, so the key never reaches the process argument list
# (`ps`), the systemd unit (world-readable), or the journal. Keep it 600 and
# owned by the lxs user.

# --- RPC authentication (comma-separated; empty = OPEN, and the node logs a
# loud warning at startup). Generate a real key, e.g.:  openssl rand -hex 32
# Multiple keys are allowed so you can rotate: add the new one, deploy, retire
# the old one on the next deploy.
LXS_RPC_API_KEYS=CHANGE-ME-openssl-rand-hex-32

# That is the only variable the binary reads from the environment. Everything
# else — bind address, p2p port, bootstrap peers, mining, CORS — is a flag on
# ExecStart in the unit file, because those are not secrets and are meant to be
# read there. To set a browser CORS allowlist, add `-rpc-cors https://your.app`
# to ExecStart; to expose the RPC publicly, bind `-rpc 0.0.0.0:8545` there AND
# make sure this key is set (never expose an unauthenticated port).
